Cell["Abstract", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"3b816fd9-320d-424a-b821-e03e8549c6f6"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "This notebook presents a pure-Wolfram-Language implementation of Blackjack. \
It ships as two packages: ",
 StyleBox["Blackjack`", "Input"],
 " contains the game engine (deck, dealer policy, scoring, payout, Hi-Lo \
counting, a Hit/Stand basic-strategy oracle, and a Monte-Carlo EV estimator), \
and ",
 StyleBox["BlackjackGame`", "Input"],
 " wraps everything in a ",
 StyleBox["DynamicModule", "Input"],
 " front-end with a full casino ruleset \[LongDash] bankroll, chip-based \
betting, 3:2 natural-blackjack payout, double-down, and splitting pairs \
(including the split-aces special case). Beyond the playable game, the \
notebook develops the probability theory of Blackjack: the chance of a \
natural (",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"P", "(", "BJ", ")"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineFormula",
  FontFamily->"Times",ExpressionUUID->
  "fe748389-ff57-4978-8e2f-71c4697c92cb"],
 " \[TildeTilde] 4.83%), the dealer's final-total distribution for each \
upcard, the Bellman formulation of the player's decision problem, the \
resulting basic-strategy table, and the Hi-Lo card counting system with its \
linear EV model and the Kelly betting criterion. Every figure in the document \
is produced by the same code that powers the game; the game itself can be \
launched from the cell at the end."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7434b890-b9d0-4251-81c7-4a9e9ae48296"],

